\section{Introduction and Related Work}

Large Language Models (LLMs) such as GPT-4 \cite{achiam2023gpt}, Gemini \cite{team2023gemini}, and Med-PaLM 2 \cite{singhal2025toward} have demonstrated strong capabilities in natural language reasoning across domains, including medicine. Recent studies report near-clinician performance on medical question-answering benchmarks \cite{kung2023performance,nori2023capabilities}, highlighting their potential for applications such as clinical decision support, documentation, and triage \cite{lee2023benefits}. However, the same properties that make LLMs powerful—large-scale training, open-ended generation, and fluent language production—also introduce reliability concerns in domains requiring factual precision, causal reasoning, and accountability \cite{ji2023survey,begoli2019need}.

In clinical practice, accuracy alone is insufficient; decisions must also be explainable and justifiable. Physicians reason through causal relationships, uncertainty, and evidence evaluation, whereas LLM outputs often lack transparent reasoning processes \cite{tonekaboni2019clinicians,amann2020explainability}. Consequently, even correct predictions may be unreliable if their underlying rationale cannot be inspected or verified.

Despite advances in alignment and safety evaluation \cite{mei2023assert}, medical LLMs still struggle with trustworthiness, which encompasses accuracy, consistency, safety, and interpretability \cite{a2019,huang2025survey}. Models frequently display unjustified confidence \cite{kadavath2022language}, produce inconsistent explanations, or fail to express uncertainty in ambiguous cases. This epistemic overconfidence is particularly problematic in medicine, where acknowledging uncertainty can be safer than confident but incorrect conclusions. Systems such as BioGPT \cite{luo2022biogpt}, Med-PaLM 2 \cite{singhal2025toward}, and ChatDoctor \cite{li2023chatdoctor} achieve strong factual performance but often exhibit unstable reasoning, where small prompt variations may lead to different diagnoses. Similar concerns have been noted in research on calibration and uncertainty estimation \cite{guo2017calibration,malinin2020uncertainty}.

Explainable AI research has attempted to address interpretability challenges through methods such as LIME \cite{ribeiro2016should}, SHAP \cite{lundberg2017unified}, and Grad-CAM \cite{selvaraju2017grad}, which attribute model predictions to input features. While useful for static models, these techniques are less suited to clinical reasoning tasks where decisions emerge through sequential evidence evaluation. Medical AI instead requires \emph{causability}—clear mappings between evidence, reasoning, and outcomes that clinicians can interpret \cite{holzinger2019causability,ahmad2018interpretable}.

Recent work on LLM reasoning has introduced techniques such as chain-of-thought prompting \cite{wei2022chain}, self-consistency \cite{wang2022self}, and reflection frameworks \cite{shinn2023reflexion}, which externalize reasoning as textual traces. However, these explanations are often post-hoc rationalizations rather than faithful representations of internal reasoning \cite{turpin2023language}. Models may produce plausible but incorrect justifications, leading to “hallucinated certainty” \cite{kadavath2022language,ji2023survey}.

In medical applications, several LLM systems—including BioGPT \cite{luo2022biogpt}, Med-PaLM 2 \cite{singhal2025toward}, and ChatDoctor \cite{li2023chatdoctor}—demonstrate promising performance but provide limited visibility into diagnostic reasoning. Interactive frameworks such as Clinical-Camel \cite{toma2023clinical} and multi-agent systems like AgentClinic \cite{schmidgall2024agentclinic} attempt to improve clinical dialogue and collaborative reasoning. However, they generally lack comprehensive reasoning audit trails and explicit mechanisms for uncertainty estimation or accountability. Safety-focused approaches such as Med-Guard \cite{jain2025medguard} detect harmful outputs but still treat reasoning as a black box.

Regulatory guidelines from the World Health Organization \cite{guidance2021ethics} and the European Commission \cite{bomhard2021regulation} emphasize transparency, traceability, and auditability as core requirements for trustworthy medical AI. Yet most LLM pipelines remain opaque during inference, limiting reproducibility, fairness auditing, and clinician trust \cite{begoli2019need,doshi2017towards}.

To address these challenges, we propose \textbf{Trust-X}, a framework designed for \textbf{trust-centered explainability in clinical reasoning}. Trust-X introduces four mechanisms:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Consensus Reasoning:} Multiple doctor agents independently analyze a case and vote on diagnoses, with disagreement quantified through the \emph{Consensus Disagreement Rate (CDR)}.
    \item \textbf{Reasoning Traces:} Each diagnostic step links evidence, reasoning, and conclusions, allowing clinicians to follow the reasoning process.
    \item \textbf{End-to-End Logging:} Agent interactions are recorded with timestamps and rationale to enable reproducibility and auditability.
    \item \textbf{Trust Scoring:} A trust layer aggregates interpretability, reasoning quality, and safety signals into measurable trust metrics.
\end{itemize}

By embedding transparency directly into the reasoning pipeline, Trust-X converts opaque LLM inference into a traceable diagnostic process. Rather than assuming model reliability, the framework \emph{reveals and measures how trust emerges—or fails—within the reasoning process}, enabling clinicians to inspect both outcomes and the reasoning paths that produced them.
